The O
purpose O
of O
std::condition_variable B-Library_Class
is O
to O
wait O
for O
some O
condition O
to O
become O
true O
. O

It O
is O
not O
designed O
to O
be O
just O
a O
receiver O
of O
a O
notify O
. O

You O
might O
use O
it O
, O
for O
example O
, O
when O
a O
consumer O
thread O
needs O
to O
wait O
for O
a O
queue B-Data_Structure
to O
become O
non-empty O
. O

CODE_BLOCK O
: O
A_2114 O
( O
code O
omitted O
for O
annotation O
) O

The O
consumer O
( O
get_from_queue O
) O
is O
not O
waiting O
for O
the O
condition B-Library_Class
variable I-Library_Class
, O
they O
are O
waiting O
for O
the O
condition O
the_queue.empty() O
. O

The O
condition B-Library_Class
variable I-Library_Class
gives O
you O
the O
way O
to O
put O
them O
to O
sleep O
while O
they O
are O
waiting O
, O
simultaneously O
releasing O
the O
mutex B-Library_Class
and O
doing O
so O
in O
a O
way O
that O
avoids O
race O
conditions O
where O
you O
miss O
wake O
ups O
. O

The O
condition O
you O
are O
waiting O
on O
should O
be O
protected O
by O
a O
mutex B-Library_Class
( O
the O
one O
you O
release O
when O
you O
wait O
on O
the O
condition B-Library_Class
variable I-Library_Class
. O
) O

This O
means O
that O
the O
condition O
rarely O
( O
if O
ever O
) O
needs O
to O
be O
an O
atomic B-Data_Type
. O

You O
are O
always O
accessing O
it O
from O
within O
a O
mutex B-Library_Class
. O

Answer_to_Question_ID O
: O
16350473 O

Question_URL O
: O

You O
can O
code O
this O
either O
way O
: O

Using O
atomics B-Data_Type
and O
a O
polling O
loop O
. O

Using O
a O
condition_variable B-Library_Class
. O

I O
've O
coded O
it O
both O
ways O
for O
you O
below O
. O

On O
my O
system O
I O
can O
monitor O
in O
real O
time O
how O
much O
cpu B-Device
any O
given O
process O
is O
using O
. O

First O
with O
the O
polling O
loop O
: O

CODE_BLOCK O
: O
A_2115 O
( O
code O
omitted O
for O
annotation O
) O

For O
me O
this O
takes O
30 O
seconds O
to O
execute O
, O
and O
while O
executing O
the O
process O
takes O
about O
99.6 O
% O
of O
a O
cpu B-Device
. O

Alternatively O
with O
a O
condition_variable B-Library_Class
: O

CODE_BLOCK O
: O
A_2116 O
( O
code O
omitted O
for O
annotation O
) O

This O
has O
the O
exact O
same O
behavior O
except O
that O
during O
the O
30 O
second O
execution O
, O
the O
process O
is O
taking O
0.0 O
% O
cpu B-Device
. O

If O
you O
're O
writing O
an O
app O
that O
might O
execute O
on O
a O
battery B-Device
powered O
device O
, O
the O
latter O
is O
nearly O
infinitely O
easier O
on O
the O
battery B-Device
. O

Now O
admittedly O
, O
if O
you O
had O
a O
very O
poor O
implementation O
of O
std::condition_variable B-Library_Class
, O
it O
could O
have O
the O
same O
inefficiency O
as O
the O
polling O
loop O
. O

However O
in O
practice O
such O
a O
vendor O
ought O
to O
go O
out O
of O
business O
fairly O
quickly O
. O

Update O

For O
grins O
I O
augmented O
my O
condition_variable B-Library_Class
wait O
loop O
with O
a O
spurious O
wakeup O
detector O
. O

I O
ran O
it O
again O
, O
and O
it O
did O
not O
print O
out O
anything O
. O

Not O
one O
spurious O
wakeup O
. O

That O
is O
of O
course O
not O
guaranteed O
. O

But O
it O
does O
demonstrate O
what O
a O
quality O
implementation O
can O
achieve O
. O

: O
36272581 O

Question_URL O

https://stackoverflow.com/questions/36272581/ O


A O
little O
preamble O
: O
Knockback B-Library
puts O
the O
model O
in O
MVVM O
, O
where O
Knockout B-Library
is O
really O
just O
VVM O
. O

Knockback B-Library
also O
gives O
you O
some O
automatic O
synchronization O
between O
them O
, O
which O
is O
nice O
. O

But O
you O
still O
need O
to O
keep O
in O
mind O
that O
the O
model O
and O
the O
viewmodel B-Library_Class
are O
two O
different O
pieces O
of O
your O
app O
. O

The O
viewmodel B-Library_Class
is O
n't O
just O
a O
Knockout B-Library
copy O
of O
the O
Bootstrap B-Library
model O
. O

Do O
n't O
put O
viewmodel B-Library_Class
pieces O
in O
the O
model O
. O

So O
you O
need O
to O
decide O
whether O
validation O
is O
a O
viewmodel B-Library_Class
behavior O
or O
a O
model O
behavior O
. O

I O
say O
viewmodel B-Library_Class
, O
because O
you O
want O
to O
use O
it O
in O
the O
view O
. O

So O
remove O
it O
from O
the O
model O
and O
define O
a O
computed O
. O

However O
, O
if O
you O
wanted O
it O
to O
be O
part O
of O
the O
model O
, O
you O
would O
want O
to O
define O
an O
attribute O
, O
not O
just O
a O
method O
, O
and O
a O
model O
event O
handler O
that O
would O
update O
the O
attribute O
on O
change O
. O

Knockback B-Library
will O
dutifully O
copy O
the O
attribute O
into O
the O
viewmodel B-Library_Class
, O
and O
you O
can O
use O
it O
there O
. O

CODE_BLOCK O
: O
Q_5182 O
( O
code O
omitted O
for O
annotation O
) O

CODE_BLOCK O
: O
Q_5183 O
( O
code O
omitted O
for O
annotation O
) O

CODE_BLOCK O
: O
Q_5184 O
( O
code O
omitted O
for O
annotation O
) O

From O
your O
description O
of O
your O
problem O
, O
I O
assume O
you O
specify O
the O
ConnectionString O
of O
the O
ADOQuery B-Library_Class
. O

Doing O
this O
combines O
the O
database O
login O
with O
the O
running O
of O
the O
query O
. O

You O
have O
found O
that O
this O
has O
undesirable O
side O
effects O
when O
the O
user O
's O
credentials O
are O
invalid O
. O

Separate O
the O
database O
login O
from O
the O
query O
by O
using O
an O
ADOConnection B-Library_Class
. O

Specify O
the O
ConnectionString O
of O
the O
ADOConnection B-Library_Class
and O
assign O
the O
ADOConnection B-Library_Class
to O
the O
ADOQuery.Connection O
property O
. O

This O
way O
, O
you O
control O
the O
database O
login O
and O
can O
catch O
logins O
with O
bad O
credentials O
. O

Additionally O
the O
ADOConnection.Open O
method O
allows O
you O
to O
specify O
the O
username O
and O
password O
so O
you O
do O
not O
have O
to O
put O
them O
in O
the O
ConnectionString O
. O

While O
this O
does O
not O
answer O
you O
specific O
questions O
, O
this O
approach O
will O
help O
you O
solve O
the O
problem O
of O
the O
user O
's O
profile O
being O
disabled O
by O
separating O
the O
login O
from O
the O
running O
of O
the O
query O
. O

The O
GameBoy B-Device
CPU I-Device
manual O
has O
it O
backwards O
. O

SUB O
, O
SBC O
and O
CP O
all O
set O
the O
carry O
flag O
when O
there O
is O
borrow O
. O

A O
, O
n O
is O
executed O
then O
carry O
is O
set O
if O
n O
> O
A O

it O
is O
clear O
. O

is O
consistent O
with O

( O
and O
8080 B-Device
) O
operation O
. O

As O
well O

countries O

of O
values O
: O
" O

Countries O
" O

" O

Countries O
" O
. O

second O
value O

shipping O
will O
be O

only O

You O
do O
n't O
have O
to O
add O
the O
intent O
filter O
for O
your O
own O
broadcasts B-Library_Class
. O

Just O
register O
the O
service B-Library_Class
for O
that O
broadcasts B-Library_Class
with O
registerReceiver() O
when O
the O
service B-Library_Class
is O
started O
. O

Note O
, O
that O
you O
have O
to O
start O
the O
service B-Library_Class
manually O
when O
your O
App O
starts O
, O
for O
instance O
in O
the O
MainActivity.onCreate() O
: O

CODE_BLOCK O
: O
A_3072 O
( O
code O
omitted O
for O
annotation O
) O

When O
the O
MainActivity O
has O
been O
created O
, O
it O
will O
start O
the O
service B-Library_Class
, O
which O
itself O
registers O
for O
BroadcastIntents B-Library_Class
and O
starts O
listening O
for O
them O
. O

This O
should O
work O
. O

the O

that O
you O

Your O
suggestion O
sounds O

to O

. O

If O

format O
is O
really O
so O
predictable O
, O
any O
more O

approaches O
might O
just O

overkill O
in O
my O
opinion O
. O

But O
if O
you O
want O
to O
see O
a O
different O
approach O
, O
this O
is O
my O
idea O
: O
Every O
line O
that O
does O
not O
start O
with O
an O
% O
is O
something O
we O
want O
to O
parse O
to O
an O
ArrayList B-Library_Class
. O

So O
, O
whenever O
you O
come O
across O
a O
line O
that O
is O
not O
a O
comment O
, O
you O
start O

following O
lines O
to O
an O
ArrayList B-Library_Class
until O
you O
either O
hit O
another O
comment O
or O
the O
end O
of O
the O
file O
. O

Both O
options O
mark O
the O
end O
of O
the O
part O

Removing O
a O
display O
object O
from O
the O
display O
list B-Data_Structure
, O
does O
n't O
stop O
the O
animation O
or O
remove O
it O
from O
memory O
. O

It O
just O
removes O
it O
from O
the O
display O
list B-Data_Structure
. O

Yes O
, O
you O
need O
to O
stop O
the O
animation O
and O
remove O
any O
event B-Library_Class
listeners O
that O
might O
be O
active O
for O
that O
object O
. O

A O
display O
object O
is O
never O
truly O
gone O
until O
it O
is O
garbage O
collected O
. O

But O
that O
will O
not O
happen O
until O
no O
references O
to O
that O
object O
remain O
. O

So O
if O
you O
have O
a O
variable O
called O
explosion O
that O
references O
your O
display O
object O
, O
you O
need O
to O
set O
it O
to O
null O
after O
removing O
it O
from O
the O
display O
list B-Data_Structure
: O

CODE_BLOCK O
: O
A_2053 O
( O
code O
omitted O
for O
annotation O
) O

Keep O
in O
mind O
that O
this O
does O
n't O
immediately O
remove O
the O
object O
from O
memory O
, O
it O
just O
makes O
it O
fair O
game O
for O
the O
garbage O
collector O
. O

You O
can O
google O
" O
AS3 B-Programming_Language
Garbage O
Collection O
" O
to O
get O
more O
information O
on O
that O
process O
. O

offers O

for O

library O
. O

and O
tested O

1.You O
are O
not O
using O
Network O
topology O
. O

2.Your O
replication O
factor O
is O
2 O
. O

Simple O
strategy O
: O

only O
for O
a O
single O
datacenter O
and O
one O
rack O
. O

SimpleStrategy O
places O
the O
first O
replica O
on O
a O
node B-Data_Structure
determined O
by O
the O
partitioner O
. O

replicas O
are O
placed O
on O
the O
next O
nodes B-Data_Structure
clockwise O
in O
the O
ring O
without O
considering O
topology O
( O
rack O
or O

location O
) O
. O

to O

running O
( O
because O
then O
audio O
data O
would O
be O
unable O
to O
be O
generated O
) O
. O

That O
's O
why O
when O
you O
stop O
the O
audio B-User_Interface_Element
graph I-User_Interface_Element
, O
2-3 O
minutes O
later O
, O
iOS B-Operating_System
will O
background O
your O
process O
( O
as O
of O
iOS B-Operating_System
9 O
) O
. O

Presumably O
, O
iOS B-Operating_System
looks O
at O
what O
's O
going O
on O
in O
your O
process O
and O
decides O
when O
your O
process O
should O
be O
forced O
to O
background O
( O
via O
beginBackgroundTaskWithName:expirationHandler O
) O
. O

Apple O
devs O
decided O

to O
make O

stop O
when O
put O
into O
background O
mode O
( O

is O
QA O
) O
. O

The O
good O
news O

that O

can O
detect O

and O

when O

process O
exits O

, O
but O

WILL O
need O
to O
restart O
your O
reader O
and O
readerOutput O
again O
. O

First O
, O

, O

The O

point O

first O

( O

already O

) O
. O

to O

your O
AVAssetReader B-Library_Class
and O

flow O

But O

You O
ca O
n't O
use O
array B-Data_Structure
syntax O
(array O
[ O
index O
] O
) O
for O
stacks B-Library_Class
, O
you O
have O
to O
use O
push() O
, O
pop() O
, O
and O
peek() O

Stacks B-Library_Class
work O
on O
a O
first-in O
, O
last-out O
basis O
. O

So O
, O
the O
only O
element O
in O
the O
stack B-Library_Class
that O
is O

is O
the O
top O
one O
. O

When O
you O
use O
pop() O
, O
you O
remove O
the O
top O
item O
so O
that O
the O
next O
can O
be O
accessed O
. O

push() O
is O
used O
to O
put O
a O
value O
on O
the O
top O
and O
peek() O
is O
used O
to O
check O
the O
top O
item O
without O
popping O
it O
. O

If O
I O
have O
the O
following O
stack B-Library_Class

CODE_BLOCK O
: O

( O
code O
omitted O
for O
annotation O
) O

" O

" O

like O

. O

code O
omitted O

" O

" O

Answer_to_Question_ID O

For O
one O
, O
your O
queue B-Data_Structure
implementation O
is O
not O
thread-safe O
at O
this O
point O
. O

Your O
question O
strongly O
suggests O
that O
this O
code O
will O
be O
used O
in O
a O
multi-threaded O
environment O
. O

Having O
a O
non O
thread-safe O
queue B-Data_Structure
will O
give O
you O
wrong O
results O
, O
and O
weird O
things O
can O
happen O
( O
like O
removeFromQueue() O
returning O
the O
same O
thing O
to O
two O
different O
threads O
, O
or O
addToQueue() O
inserting O
two O
items O
in O
the O
same O
position O
) O
. O

Aside O
from O
that O
, O
your O
queue B-Data_Structure
implementation O
would O
never O
work O
. O

You O
are O
not O
using O
front O
and O
rear O
correctly O
. O

Look O
carefully O
at O
the O
insert O
function O
: O

CODE_BLOCK O
: O
A_3531 O
( O
code O
omitted O
for O
annotation O
) O

You O
check O
if O
rear O
is O
MAX O
, O
yet O
, O
you O
write O
into O
queue[front] O
and O
increment O
front O
. O

What O
if O
I O
just O
keep O
adding O
items O
to O
the O
queue O
, O
eventually O
reaching O
the O
buffer O
's O
limit O
? O

rear O
will O
always O
be O
0 O
, O
front O
will O
grow O
indefinitely O
, O
and O
your O
function O
will O
write O
beyond O
the O
limits O
of O
queue B-Data_Structure
. O

That O
's O
probably O
the O
cause O
of O
your O
segmentation O
fault O
errors O
. O

I O
think O
you O
wanted O
to O
check O
for O
front O
instead O
: O

CODE_BLOCK O
: O
A_3532 O
( O
code O
omitted O
for O
annotation O
) O

The O
code O
for O
removeFromQueue() O
looks O
superficially O
ok O
, O
as O
long O
as O
queue B-Data_Structure
is O
a O
global B-Data_Type
array B-Data_Structure
( O
since O
you O
're O
returning O
a O
pointer B-Data_Type
, O
and O
ca O
n't O
return O
pointers B-Data_Type
to O
local O
variables O
) O
. O

However O
, O
the O
single O
, O
most O
important O
fact O
you O
have O
to O
take O
out O
of O
this O
answer O
, O
is O
that O
your O
queue B-Data_Structure
implementation O
will O
not O
scale O
in O
the O
long-term O
. O

An O
array-based O
queue B-Data_Structure
is O
a O
terrible O
choice O
. O

What O
do O
you O
do O
when O
you O
run O
out O
of O
space O
in O
the O
array B-Data_Structure
? O

What O
if O
I O
insert O
MAX O
elements O
, O
then O
remove O
2 O
or O
3 O
, O
and O
try O
to O
insert O
more O
? O

Your O
code O
will O
say O
the O
queue B-Data_Structure
is O
full O
, O
because O
it O
only O
ever O
allows O
you O
to O
insert O
MAX O
elements O
in O
total O
. O

You O
could O
shift O
every O
element O
in O
the O
queue B-Data_Structure
to O
the O
left O
when O
an O
element O
is O
removed O
, O
but O
that O
's O
crazy O
, O
and O
extremely O
inefficient O
. O

Or O
you O
could O
increment O
front O
modulo O
MAX O
, O
allowing O
rear O
to O
be O
ahead O
of O
front O
, O
as O
long O
as O
you O
know O
that O
no O
more O
than O
MAX O
elements O
can O
be O
inserted O
. O

That O
would O
be O
better O
, O
but O
it O
would O
break O
the O
logic O
in O
removeFromQueue() O
, O
since O
the O
pointers B-Data_Type
returned O
earlier O
will O
possibly O
point O
to O
a O
different O
thread O
struct B-Data_Structure
as O
you O
manipulate O
the O
queue B-Data_Structure
- O
total O
disaster O
. O

Definitely O
not O
what O
you O
want O
. O

A O
much O
, O
much O
better O
approach O
would O
be O
to O
implement O
this O
with O
a O
linked B-Data_Structure
list I-Data_Structure
where O
you O
keep O
a O
pointer B-Data_Type
to O
the O
head O
and O
a O
pointer B-Data_Type
to O
the O
tail O
. O

Have O
a O
look O
at O
http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Queue_(abstract_data_type)#Queue_implementation O

In O
C# B-Programming_Language
I O
usually O
prefix O
with O
_ O
private O
fields O
but O
never O
local O
variables O
. O

The O
rationale O
behind O
this O
is O
that O
when O
I O
need O
a O
private O
variable O
I O
type O
_ O
and O
the O
Intellisense B-Application
filters O
the O
list O
and O
it O
is O
easier O
to O
find O
. O

This O
way O
I O
am O
also O
able O
to O
distinguish O
between O
private O
from O
local O
variables O
and O
I O
no O
longer O
need O
to O
type O
this.variablename O
for O
class O
fields O
but O
simply O
_variablename O
. O

your O
debugging O
session O
normally O
. O

Then O
once O
it O
is O
started O
, O
use O
Visual B-Application
Studio I-Application
, O
File/Open O
menu B-User_Interface_Element
to O
open O
the O
correct O
.cs O
file O
. O

you O
have O
a O
corresponding O
.pdb O
file O
for O

which O

be O

in O
your O
debugging O
session O
. O

you O
do O
n't O
have O
the O
pdb O
file O
, O
this O

your O
dll O
was O

debug O
configuration O
. O

you O
may O
need O
to O
open O
other O
.cs O

manually O
as O
you O
step O
into O
statements O
. O

Open O
the O
needed O
files O
before O
you O
step O
into O
them O
. O

Well O
, O

, O

When O
you O
have O
an O
assignment O
operator O
in O
a O
statement O
, O
the O
LHS O
of O
the O
operator O
must O
be O
something O
the O
language O
calls O
an O
lvalue O
. O

of O

to O
an O

to O
the O
LHS O
. O

cannot O
use O
: O

: O

( O
code O
omitted O
for O
annotation O
) O

since O
10 O
does O
not O
evaluate O
to O
an O
lvalue O
. O

can O

: O

( O
code O
omitted O
for O
annotation O
) O

since O

Question_URL O
: O
https://stackoverflow.com/questions/17604481/ O


To O
have O
WebRTC B-Application
capabilities O
on O
IE B-Application
, O
users O
could O
install O
Chrome B-Application
Frame O
( O
for O
IE6+ B-Application
) O
. O

It O
is O
a O
valid O
option O
, O
but O
you O
should O
know O
that O
it O
is O
no O
longer O
being O
actively O
supported O
by O
Google B-Website
. O

As O
far O
as O
I O
know O
, O
there O
is O
no O
automatic O
switching O
library O
. O

However O
, O
on O
your O
server O
, O
you O
could O
look O
at O
the O
HTTP O
requests O
and O
find O
out O
the O
client B-Application
's O
browser I-Application
. O

From O
there O
, O
you O
could O
dynamically O
load O
either O
the O
WebRTC B-Application
or O
Flash B-Application
library O
depending O
on O
the O
browser B-Application
's O
support O
for O
WebRTC B-Application
. O

Currently O
, O
the O
OpenTok B-Library
WebRTC B-Application
library O
supports O
: O

Chrome B-Application
23+ O

Firefox B-Application
22+ O

Unfortunately O
, O
OpenTok B-Library
does O
not O
interoperate O
between O
Flash B-Application
and O
WebRTC B-Application
clients I-Application
. O

WebRTC B-Application
clients O
can O
operate O
with O
other O
WebRTC B-Application
clients O
( O
mobile O
, O
web O
, O
etc O
. O
) O
, O
just O
like O
Flash B-Application
can O
only O
operate O
with O
other O
Flash B-Application
clients O
. O

For O
example O
, O
an O
iOS B-Operating_System
client O
would O
have O
to O
use O
the O
WebRTC B-Application
SDK I-Application
and O
the O
Chrome/Firefox B-Application
web O
app O
would O
have O
to O
include O
the O
WebRTC B-Application
Javascript B-Programming_Language
library O
. O

Answer_to_Question_ID O
: O
33886034 O

Question_URL O
: O
https://stackoverflow.com/questions/33886034/ O


It O
appears O
the O
Nios B-Device
II I-Device
architecture O
does O
n't O
have O
atomic O
test-and-set O
instructions O
. O

Instead O
for O
synchronization O
of O
shared O
resources O
between O
multiple O
Nios B-Device
II I-Device
processors O
, O
the O
architecture O
uses O
an O
" O
Hardware O
Mutex O
Core O
" O
. O

It O
works O
as O
a O
shared O
peripheral O
that O
provides O
an O
atomic O
test-and-test O
operation O
. O

You O
can O
read O
more O
about O
it O
in O
Altera O
's O
Creating O
Multiprocessor O
Nios B-Device
II I-Device
Systems O
Tutorial O
. O

However O
, O
you O
probably O
do O
n't O
an O
atomic O
test-and-set O
operation O
. O

You O
can O
make O
any O
sequence O
of O
instructions O
atomic O
with O
respect O
to O
interrupts O
on O
a O
single O
core O
system O
simply O
by O
disabling O
interrupts O
. O

Answer_to_Question_ID O
: O
32202478 O

Question_URL O
: O
https://stackoverflow.com/questions/32202478/ O


The O
schemaLocation O
does O
not O
matter O
but O
your O
input O
sample O
has O
the O
default O
namespace O
declaration O
xmlns O
= O
" O
http://www.w3schools.com O
" O
on O
the O
root O
element O
which O
puts O
all O
elements O
in O
that O
namespace O
. O

Your O
XSLT B-Programming_Language
however O
uses O
paths O
like O
school/personen/person O
which O
( O
in O
XSLT/XPath B-Programming_Language
1.0 O
) O
select O
elements O
in O
no O
namespace O
. O

Either O
move O
to O
an O
XSLT B-Programming_Language
2.0 O
processor O
where O
you O
can O
then O
define O

= O

In O
this O
example O
, O
cache O
is O
actually O
useless O
. O

You O
only O
write O
to O
it O
and O
never O
read O
from O
it O
. O

hash O
is O
being O
used O
as O
the O
actual O
cache O
here O
. O

If O
an O
image B-User_Interface_Element
with O
the O
same O
URL O
already O
exists O
, O
it O
will O
be O
returned O
from O
the O
hash O
object O
, O
and O
not O
created O
again O
. O

The O
.Single() O
is O
what O
's O
throwing O
the O
exception B-Library_Class
. O

Either O
your O
query O
is O
returning O
no O
items O
or O
it O
's O
returning O
> O
1 O
item O
. O

If O
you O
're O
not O
sure O
of O
the O
number O
of O
items O
you O
're O
expecting O
, O
you O
should O
be O
using O
FirstOrDefault() O
which O
will O
return O
the O
first O
match O
or O
null O
if O
no O
matches O
are O
found O
. O

The O
non-LINQ B-Library
equivalent O
is O
something O
like O
this O

CODE_BLOCK O
: O
A_832 O
( O
code O
omitted O
for O
annotation O
) O

Yes O
this O
is O
possible O
. O

You O
need O
to O
run O
a O
webserver B-Application
or O
loadbalancer B-Application
listening O
to O
port B-Device
443 O
and O
forwarding O
requests O
appropriately O
. O

In O
Apache B-Application
for O
example O
this O
would O
be O
handled O
as O
follows O
: O

CODE_BLOCK O
: O
A_6665 O
( O
code O
omitted O
for O
annotation O
) O

Now O
while O
Apache B-Application
does O
support O
HTTP/2 O
in O
both O
the O
front O
end O
client O
connections O
and O
the O
back O
end O
ProxyPass O
requests O
( O
with O
mod_proxy_http O
2) O
, O
some O
other O
webservers/loadbalancers B-Application
do O
n't O
( O
e.g O
. O
Nginx B-Application
) O
. O

To O
be O
honest O
most O
of O
the O
benefits O
for O
HTTP/2 O
are O
in O
the O
client O
to O
edge O
. O

So O
if O
you O
prefer O
to O
use O
Nginx B-Application
for O
example O
, O
you O
could O
just O
have O
Nginx B-Application
support O
HTTP/2 O
, O
and O
the O
connection O
from O
Nginx B-Application
to O
your O
back O
end O
apps O
be O
plain O
old O
HTTP/1.1 O
. O

At O
least O
until O
HTTP/2 O
becomes O
more O
regularly O
supported O
. O

See O
here O
for O
more O
discussion O
on O
this O
: O
HTTP2 O
with O
node.js B-Application
behind O
nginx B-Application
proxy O

Answer_to_Question_ID O
: O
37790195 O

Question_URL O
: O
https://stackoverflow.com/questions/37790195/ O


This O
is O
a O
clear O
case O
of O
metadata O
vs O
. O
data O
: O

Option O
1 O
: O
Attributes O
are O
supposed O
to O
hold O
metadata O
about O
the O
entities O
they O
are O
attached O
to O
. O

Option O
2 O
: O
member O
fields O
and O
properties O
, O
regardless O
if O
instance O
or O
static B-Data_Type
, O
are O
supposed O
to O
hold O
data O
that O
make O
up O
the O
integral O
value O
of O
the O
class O
. O

Hence O
, O
option O
1 O
, O
attributes O
, O
is O
the O
right O
approach O
to O
represent O
metadata O
. O

Usage O
of O
reflection O
is O
a O
mere O
technicality O
and O
can O
be O
encapsulated O
into O
a O
separate O
class O
, O
e.g O
. O

an O
AttributeManager O
, O
that O
would O
ease O
access O
to O
metadata O
and O
cache O
them O
appropriately O
to O
avoid O
performance O
overhead O
( O
should O
that O
be O
an O
issue O
in O
a O
particular O
case O
) O
. O

rand.Next() O
% O

will O

a O
number O
between O
0 O
and O
14 O
. O

( O

, O

and O

Problem O
with O
long O
running O
context O
is O
that O
it O
does O

refresh O
data O
- O
I O
more O

here O
. O

the O
list O
and O

. O

But O

WPF B-Library
if O

action O
is O
: O

Open O
the O
list B-Data_Structure

as O

changes O

Then O
this O
whole O
is O

of O

can O

context O
instance O
for O
that O
. O

with O

. O

- O

will O

fresh O

for O
next O
unit O
of O
work O
. O

( O

. O

Take O
the O
following O
insertion O
sort O
algorithm O
: O

I O
know O
it O
's O
O(n^2) O
fairly O
easy O
by O
examining O
it O
. O

But O
as O
far O
as O
proving O
it O
's O
O(n^2) O
, O
how O
would O
I O

about O

? O

, O

n O
+ O
" O

Answer_to_Question_ID O
: O
18972385 O

Question_URL O
: O
https://stackoverflow.com/questions/18972385/ O


It O
's O
O(n^2) O
because O
you O
've O
got O
a O
multiplication O
, O
not O
a O
sum O
. O

Take O
by O
example O
, O
an O
array B-Data_Structure
sorted O
in O
inverse O
order O
: O

CODE_BLOCK O
: O
A_2513 O
( O
code O
omitted O
for O
annotation O
) O

In O
these O
cases O
every O
iteration O
of O
the O
inner O
loop O
will O
scan O
and O
shift O
the O
entire O
sorted O
subsection O
of O
the O
array B-Data_Structure
before O
inserting O
the O
next O
element O
. O

This O
gives O
insertion O
sort O
a O
quadratic O
running O
time O
( O
i.e O
. O
, O
O(n2)) O
. O

More O
info O

The O
best O
way O
to O
understand O
the O
complexity O
is O
trying O
to O
find O
the O
worst O
case O
example O
and O
following O
the O
algorithm O
's O
steps O
. O

Answer_to_Question_ID O
: O
18972385 O

Question_URL O
: O
https://stackoverflow.com/questions/18972385/ O


You O
prove O
big O
O O
complexity O
by O
considering O
how O
many O
operations O
are O
performed O
in O
the O
worst O
case O
. O

You O
've O
done O
the O
counting O
part O
and O
entered O
the O
results O
in O
the O
right O
hand O
column B-User_Interface_Element
of O
your O
image B-User_Interface_Element
, O
so O
what O
remains O
to O
be O
proven O
is O
that O
the O
dominant O
term O
is O
O(n^2) O
. O

Apart O
from O
the O
terms O
that O
involve O
the O
sum O
, O
your O
program O
consists O
of O
instructions O
that O
get O
executed O
n-1 O
times O
so O
these O
are O
all O
O(n) O
terms O
. O

Now O
for O
the O
terms O
with O
the O
sum O
. O

In O
the O
worst O
case O
a O
t_j O
can O
be O
j O
because O
you O
may O
end O
up O
decrementing O
i O
which O
you O
set O
to O
j O
all O
the O
way O
down O
to O
0 O
. O

So O
in O
this O
worst O
case O
we O
have O
t_j O
= O
j O
and O
then O
you O
have O
a O
term O
with O
a O
sum O
from O
2 O
to O
n O
of O
j O
which O
is O
O(n^2) O
. O

This O
is O
due O
to O
following O
the O
mathematical O
identity O
: O

This O
can O
be O
proven O
by O
summing O
two O
of O
these O
series O
together O
, O
paying O
attention O
so O
that O
you O
add O
two O
terms O
that O
sum O
to O
n+1 O
together O
, O
and O
then O
dividing O
the O
sum O
by O
two O
. O

Have O
a O
look O
at O
the O
proof O
in O
wolfram B-Application
. O

Finally O
, O
since O
O O
( O
( O
n^2 O
+ O
n O
) O
/2 O
) O
= O
O(n^2) O
you O
get O
that O
the O
terms O
that O
include O
the O
sum O
dominate O
the O
runtime O
and O
that O
is O
why O
the O
algorithm O
is O
O(n^2) O

Answer_to_Question_ID O
: O
16994398 O

Question_URL O
: O
https://stackoverflow.com/questions/16994398/ O


Ruby B-Programming_Language
is O
an O
object-oriented O
language O
. O

In O
an O
object-oriented O
language O
, O
you O
send O
messages O
to O
objects O
and O
those O
objects O
then O
respond O
to O
those O
messages O
however O
they O
see O
fit O
. O

This O
means O
that O
the O
receiver O
of O
the O
message O
, O
and O
only O
the O
receiver(!) O

is O
in O
total O
control O
of O
what O
a O
message O
means O
. O

With O
some O
operators O
, O
however O
, O
there O
are O
certain O
expectations O
of O
symmetry O
: O
for O
example O
, O
a O
== O
b O
is O
expected O
to O
be O
the O
same O
as O
b O
== O
a O
. O

But O
in O
an O
OO O
language O
that O
is O
impossible O
! O

Either O
a O
or O
b O
must O
be O
the O
receiver O
of O

message O
, O
so O

. O

, O

. O

So O
, O

: O

OP_BLOCK O
: O
( O
output O
omitted O
for O
annotation O
) O

Here O

: O

. O

With O

. O

In O

, O

and O

are O
different O
. O

! O

The O

, O
i.e O
. O
the O

it O

But O

is O
not O
recorded O
in O

( O

, O

. O

There O
, O

, O

, O
and O

type O
and O

more O
: O

of O

. O

( O

: O
this O

, O

. O
) O

In O

, O
where O

. O

You O

. O

That O
's O

are O
seeing O
above O
. O

If O

, O

== O

. O

But O

, O
then O
maybe O

? O

Note O
that O
equality O
is O
very O
hard O
to O
get O
right O
. O

People O
cannot O
even O
agree O
on O
what O
it O
means O
in O
a O
purely O

language O
, O
and O
that O
's O

easy O
case O
! O

In O
Ruby B-Programming_Language
, O
there O
are O
two O
additional O
complications O
: O

state O
and O
OO O
. O

Mutable O
state O
means O
that O

that O
were O
equal O
a O

may O
not O
be O

anymore O

of O

later O
. O

Or O
should O
they O
be O
? O

Or O
should O

they O
be O
? O

And O
OO O
means O
that O
equality O
cannot O
be O

. O

That O
's O
why O
the O
implementations O
of O
== O
for O

and O

. O

That O

. O

Sometimes O

of O

, O

. O

By O

: O

. O

For O

( O

Ruby B-Programming_Language
has O
four O
levels O
of O
object O
equivalence O
: O

#equal O
? O
– O
same O
object O

#eql O
? O
– O
highest O
level O
of O
equivalence O
below O
same O
object O

# O
== O
– O
" O
standard O
" O
equality O

# O
== O
= O
, O
# O
= O
~ O
, O
#hash O
, O
etc O
. O

– O
loose O
equivalence O
, O
" O
same O
group O
" O
equivalence O

Mindful O
programmer O
equips O
each O
of O
her O
classes O
with O
all O
of O
these O
methods O
except O
#equal O
? O
, O
which O
should O
never O
be O
overriden O
. O

Going O
back O
to O
the O
subject O
of O
your O
question O
, O
many O
built-in O
Ruby B-Programming_Language
objects O
have O
their O
share O
of O
idiosyncrasies O
in O
the O
implementation O
of O
these O
methods O
. O

Ruby B-Programming_Language
core O
team O
constantly O
works O
to O
improve O
them O
, O
so O
you O
should O
make O
your O
way O
from O
1.8 O
to O
2.0 O
, O
which O
fixes O
a O
number O
of O
1.8 O
problems O
. O

One O
more O
thing O
to O
mention O
with O
# O
== O
method O
, O
is O
that O
for O
the O
classes O
that O
represent O
elements O
of O
ordered O
sets O
, O
you O
do O
not O
implement O
# O
== O
directly O
, O
but O
instead O
you O
provide O
#<=> O
three-way O
comparison O
method, O
and O
include O
Comparable B-Library
module, O
which O
gives O
you O
for O
free O
methods O
such O
as O
#==, O
#<, O
#> O
, O
#sort O
, O
etc O
. O

Yet O
one O
more O
thing O
to O
mention O
with O
all O
of O
these O
operators O
and O
operator-like O
methods O
, O
be O
mindful O
of O
the O
existence O
of O
#coerce O
method O
, O
which O
is O
currently O
undergoing O
improvements O
in O
Ruby B-Programming_Language
2.0 O
. O

Answer_to_Question_ID O
: O
44664171 O

Question_URL O

https://stackoverflow.com/questions/44664171/ O


When O
you O
use O
server B-Application
side O
rendering O
, O
you O
cannot O
close O
the O
" O
chain O
" O
you O
are O
refering O
to O
as O
easily O
. O

This O
is O
because O
what O
Django B-Library
does O
in O
this O
case O
is O
serve O
all O
the O
HTML B-Programming_Language
and O
JS B-Programming_Language
( O
at O
leas O
the O
JS B-Programming_Language
inside O
your O
HTML B-Programming_Language
view O
) O
in O
a O
single O
initial O
response O
. O

The O
ajax O
requests O
you O
do O
after O
that O
will O
not O
be O
bound O
to O
the O
variables O
you O
send O
initially O
in O
your O
response O
because O
this O
variables O
are O
populated O
when O
the O
render() O
function O
is O
called O
. O

After O
that O
moment O
, O
you O
cannot O
add O
or O
update O
the O
variables O
that O
were O
sent O
to O
the O
HTML B-Programming_Language
template O
. O

The O
only O
way O
you O
can O
manage O
rendering O
small O
parts O
of O
HTML B-Programming_Language
is O
using O
JQuery B-Library
or O
making O
your O
backend O
a O
REST O
API O
with O
Django B-Library
Rest O
Framework O
and O
moving O
to O
a O
more O
complete O
frontend O
framework O
like O
Angular B-Library
or O
React B-Library
. O

The O
are O
many O
discussions O
over O
server B-Application
side O
rendering O
vs O
client B-Application
side O
rendering O
. O

You O
can O
read O
more O
about O
it O
here O
: O

https://medium.com/@adamzerner/client-side-rendering-vs-server-side-rendering-a32d2cf3bfcc O

within O
the O

. O

follows O

35528780 O

OP_BLOCK O
: O
( O
output O
omitted O
for O
annotation O
) O

Because O
you O
threw O
string B-Data_Type
literal O
which O
decays O
to O
const B-Data_Type
char* I-Data_Type
. O

In O
short O
, O
you O
catch O
what O
you O
throw O
. O

OP_BLOCK O
: O
( O
output O
omitted O
for O
annotation O
) O

It O
does O
, O
but O
to O
catch O
string B-Data_Type
, O
you O
need O
to O
throw O
string B-Data_Type
in O
first O
place O
. O

OP_BLOCK O
: O
( O
output O
omitted O
for O
annotation O
) O

You O
can O
throw O
literally O
anything O
. O

It O
is O
a O
good O
idea O
to O
throw O
special O
exception B-Library_Class
classes O
, O
like O
std::exception B-Library_Class
and O
derived O
from O
it O
. O

OP_BLOCK O
: O
( O
output O
omitted O
for O
annotation O
) O

Yes O
, O
it O
does O
. O

OP_BLOCK O
: O
( O
output O
omitted O
for O
annotation O
) O

If O
you O
want O
, O
you O
can O
do O
that O
. O

There O
are O
not O
much O
cases O
where O
doing O
it O
is O
a O
good O
idea O
. O

It O
looks O
like O
you O
need O
to O
get O
a O
good O
book O
and O
read O
chapter O
about O
exceptions B-Library_Class
. O

In O
the O
meantime O
this O
super-FAQ O
entry O
might O
help O
you/ O

Answer_to_Question_ID O
: O
35528780 O

Question_URL O
: O
https://stackoverflow.com/questions/35528780/ O


You O
can O
throw O
an O
object O
of O
any O
type O
. O

EDIT O
: O
( O
Hopefully O
I O
got O
this O
right O
now O
) O

What O
you O
have O
done O
is O
throw O
a O
C-string B-Data_Structure
, O
which O
is O
of O
type O
const B-Data_Type
char[13] I-Data_Type
in O
this O
case O
. O

C-Arrays B-Data_Structure
will O
decay O
to O
pointers O
to O
their O
first O
element O
, O
in O
this O
case O
a O
pointer O
of O
type O
const B-Data_Type
char* I-Data_Type
. O

Typically O
what O
you O
want O
to O
do O
is O
throw O
a O
predefined O
exception B-Library_Class
object O
. O

They O
can O
be O
found O
in O
header O
<stdexcept> B-Library_Class
and O
are O
derived O
from O
a O
base O
class O
std::exception B-Library_Class
. O

The O
derived O
exception B-Library_Class
classes O
are O
for O
instance O
std::logic_error B-Library_Class
, O
std::range_error B-Library_Class
, O
std::bad_alloc B-Library_Class
etc O
. O

Their O
constructors O
take O
a O
string B-Data_Type
as O
argument O
, O
so O
you O
can O
for O
instance O

CODE_BLOCK O
: O
A_5063 O
( O
code O
omitted O
for O
annotation O
) O

This O
message O
can O
be O
accessed O
in O
a O
catch O
statement O
like O
this O
: O

CODE_BLOCK O
: O
A_5064 O
( O
code O
omitted O
for O
annotation O
) O

If O
an O
exception B-Library_Class
is O
caught O
, O
so-called O
stack B-Data_Structure
unwinding O
takes O
place O
. O

You O
can O
then O
deal O
with O
the O
error O
locally O
, O
or O
rethrow O
the O
exception B-Library_Class
. O

Only O
when O
an O
exception B-Library_Class
is O
thrown O
and O
never O
caught O
, O
std::terminate() O
is O
called O
an O
the O
program O
aborted O
. O

You O
can O
put O
try/catch O
statements O
anywhere O
. O

However O
, O
remember O
what O
the O
term O
" O
exception B-Library_Class
" O
actually O
means O
. O

Cases O
that O
can O
easily O
dealt O
with O
using O
a O
simple O
conditional O
expression O
if O
( O
n O
< O
0 O
) O
break O
; O
or O
something O
like O
that O
, O
do O
n't O
need O
the O
exception B-Library_Class
treatment O
. O

Especially O
if O
you O
can O
realistically O
expect O
this O
kind O
of O
unwanted O
condition O
to O
be O
true O
often O
. O

Then O
it O
is O
not O
something O
" O
exceptional O
" O
. O

If O
you O
decide O
to O
deal O
with O
an O
error O
using O
exceptions B-Library_Class
and O
they O
can O
not O
be O
treated O
locally O
, O
you O
may O
put O
try/catch O
clauses O
around O
the O
beginning O
and O
end O
of O
main() O
. O

Since O
you O
can O
put O
several O
catch O
statements O
directly O
after O
a O
try O
statement O
, O
you O
can O
then O
begin O
to O
deal O
with O
more O
specific O
errors O
, O
or O
simply O
catch O
anything O
via O
catch(...) O
{ O
//.. O
. O
} O
. O

This O
is O
all O
described O
in O
great O
detail O
( O
including O
pointers B-Data_Type
on O
when O
and O
when O
not O
to O
use O
it O
, O
in O
the O
C++ B-Programming_Language
FAQ O
. O

EDIT O
: O
Here O
's O
an O
example O
that O
makes O
use O
of O
try/catch O
statements O
. O

However O
, O
not O
an O
exception B-Library_Class
object O
is O
caught O
, O
but O
an O
int B-Data_Type
( O
errno O
) O
. O

Just O
to O
show O
, O
that O
you O
can O
really O
throw/catch O
anything O
you O
like O
. O

Let O
process_several_files() O
be O
a O
function O
somewhere O
nested O
in O
your O
code O
: O

Answer_to_Question_ID O
: O
31243125 O

Question_URL O
: O
https://stackoverflow.com/questions/31243125/ O


This O
is O
because O
of O
a O
deadlock O
. O

SignalR B-Library
client B-Application
blocks O
the O
thread O
when O
sending O
the O
Abort O
request O
. O

However O
Silverlight B-Library
wants O
to O
send O
the O
request O
on O
the O
UI O
thread O
. O

The O
default O
timeout O
for O
stopping O
the O
connection O
is O
30 O
seconds O
so O
after O
the O
timeout O
the O
thread O
is O
unblocked O
and O
execution O
continues O
. O

This O
can O
be O
worked O
around O
by O
invoking O
stop O
asynchronously O
( O
await O
Task.Factory.StartNew O
(() O
=> O
hubConnection.Stop());) O
or O
making O
the O
timeout O
smaller O
. O

TL O
;D O
R O
; O

https://github.com/SignalR/SignalR/issues/3102 O

https://stackoverflow.com/questions/31243125/ O

method O
in O
Silverlight B-Library
Threading O
task O
. O

now O
I O
do O
not O
worry O
about O
acknowledgement O
of O
hub O
disconnect O
from O

. O

in O
your O
gsub O
call O
, O
" O
. O
" O
is O
your O
pattern O
. O

The O
" O
. O
" O
symbol O
in O
a O
pattern O
means O
" O
any O
character O
" O
, O
so O
you O
're O
talling O
gsub O
to O
replace O
every O
character O
with O
a O
dash O
. O

The O
correct O
gsub O
call O
requires O
escaping O
the O
period O
so O
R B-Programming_Language
knows O
this O
is O
a O
literal O
period O
: O

CODE_BLOCK O
: O
A_2193 O
( O
code O
omitted O
for O
annotation O
) O

This O
syntax O
will O
have O
gsub O
replace O
all O
periods O
with O
dashes O
. O

But O
really O
, O
this O
is O
n't O
what O
you O
want O
, O
you O
want O
dates O
. O

You O
need O
to O
use O
as.Date O
like O
so O
: O

CODE_BLOCK O
: O
A_2194 O
( O
code O
omitted O
for O
annotation O
) O

Your O
intended O
solution O
would O
only O
have O
converted O
your O
strings B-Data_Type
to O
a O
different O
string B-Data_Type
format O
. O

Using O
as.Date O
tells O
R B-Programming_Language
to O
treat O
the O
values O
as O
dates O
and O
not O
strings B-Data_Type
. O

CODE_BLOCK O
: O
A_2195 O
( O
code O
omitted O
for O
annotation O
) O

will O
produce O
an O
error O
( O
because O
R B-Programming_Language
does O
n't O
understand O
what O
you O
want O
when O
you O
ask O
it O
to O
plot O
nothing O
but O
strings B-Data_Type
) O
, O
whereas O
: O

CODE_BLOCK O
: O
A_2196 O
( O
code O
omitted O
for O
annotation O
) O

a O
plot O
of O
index O
vs O
. O
day O
of O
the O
week O
( O
since O
R B-Programming_Language

) O

From O

, O

. O

cart O

like O
this O
: O

At O
time O
0 O
we O
have O
our O
initial O
cart O
- O
call O
it O
cart0 O

At O
time O
t O
, O
we O
submit O
n O
simultaneous O
requests O
to O
add/update/change O
the O
cart O

Request O
0 O
: O
take O
cart0 O
and O
apply O
request O
, O
return O
result O

Request O
1 O
: O
take O
cart0 O
and O
apply O
request O
, O
return O
result O

.. O
. O

Request O
n O
: O
take O
cart0 O
and O
apply O
request O
, O
return O
result O

This O
seems O
consistent O
with O
the O
cart O
return O
values O
that O
I O
got O
when O

tested O

requests O
at O

same O
time O
- O
each O
callback O
function O
would O
trigger O
with O
a O

a O
single O
change O
applied O
. O

I O
've O
found O
two O

to O

with O
this O

. O

The O
first O

to O

the O

. O

Not O

best O
for O

. O

The O

only O

do O

have O

to O

about O
: O

/cart/update.js O
, O

all O
at O
once O
- O
see O
https://help.shopify.com/themes/development/getting-started/using-ajax-api#update-cart O
for O

. O

If O
you O
do O

have O
line O
properties O
to O
worry O
about O
, O

. O

This O
happens O
when O
one O
of O
the O
objects O
you O
're O
linking O
into O
an O
executable O
changes O
significantly O
. O

For O
example O
it O
gains O
or O
loses O
some O
lines O
of O
profilable O
code O
. O

The O
minimal O
case O
to O
produce O
the O
error O
is O
with O
2 O
source O
files O
. O

Here O
are O
2 O
example O
source O
files O
called O
c O
.. O
. O

CODE_BLOCK O
: O
A_260 O
( O
code O
omitted O
for O
annotation O
) O

and O
stuff.c O

CODE_BLOCK O
: O
A_261 O
( O
code O
omitted O
for O
annotation O
) O

What O
they O
do O
is O
n't O
important O
. O

To O
build O
them O
, O
here O
is O
a O
simple O
Makefile O
: O

CODE_BLOCK O
: O
A_262 O
( O
code O
omitted O
for O
annotation O
) O

The O
Makefile O
is O
set O
up O
so O
that O
the O
compilation O
is O
main.c O
-> O
main.o O
, O
stuff.c O
-> O
stuff.o O
and O
finally O
stuff.o O
+ O
main.o O
-> O
testexe O
. O

If O
we O
compile O
and O
link O
those O
C B-Programming_Language
files O
with O
the O
-fprofile-arcs O
-ftest-coverage O
options O
then O
the O
executable O
file O
has O
profiling O
. O

Run O
that O
execuatable O
and O
you O
'll O
get O
2 O
output O
files O
, O
main.gcda O
and O
stuff.gcda O
. O

So O
far O
so O
good O
. O

Now O
change O
the O
line O
#if O
0 O
to O
#if O
1 O
. O

The O
Makefile O
should O
cause O
just O
stuff.c O
to O
recompile O
, O
and O
the O
executable O
to O
relink O
. O

Next O
time O

test O
executable O

run O

'll O
get O

" O
Merge O
mismatch O
" O

for O

main.gcda O
file O
. O

The O
stuff.gcda O
file O
is O
not O
affected O
since O
its O
object O
file O
has O
been O
recreated O
with O
all O
the O
new O
summary O
information O
. O

If O
you O
recompile O
main.c O
and O
relink O
the O
executable O
, O
then O

message O

. O

So O

? O

I O

! O

' O

rm O

That O
regex O
is O
not O
legal O
in O
sed O
; O
since O
it O
uses O
Perl B-Programming_Language
syntax O
, O
my O
recommendation O
would O
be O
to O
use O
perl B-Programming_Language
instead O
. O

The O
regular O
expression O
works O
exactly O
as-is O
, O
and O
even O
the O
command B-Application
line I-Application
is O
almost O
the O
same O
; O
you O
just O
need O
to O
add O
the O
-p O
option O
to O
get O
perl B-Programming_Language
to O
operate O
in O
filter O
mode O
( O
which O
sed O
does O
by O
default O
) O
. O

I O
would O
also O
recommend O
adding O
an O
argument O
suffix O
to O
the O
-i O
option O
( O
whether O
using O
sed O
or O
perl B-Programming_Language
) O
, O
so O
that O
you O
have O
a O
backup O
of O
the O
original O
file O
in O
case O
something O
goes O
horribly O
wrong O
. O

As O
for O
quoting O
, O
all O
you O
need O
to O
do O
is O
put O
the O
substitution O
command O
in O
single O
quotation O
marks O
: O

CODE_BLOCK O
: O
A_6411 O
( O
code O
omitted O
for O
annotation O
) O

Answer_to_Question_ID O
: O
10662029 O

Question_URL O
: O
https://stackoverflow.com/questions/10662029/ O


Lazy-loading O
seems O
most O
suitable O
for O
smaller O
apps O
without O
separate O
data O
layers O
. O

Once O
the O
app O
grows O
and O
you O
start O
separating O
it O
into O
separate O
layers O
, O
lazy O
loading O
becomes O
less O
useful O
. O

The O
DBcontext B-Library_Class
has O
long O
since O
been O
destroyed O
by O
the O
time O
the O
data O
gets O
to O
the O
UI O
layer O
, O
and O
while O
you O
are O
within O
the O
datalayer O
it O
is O
not O
a O
big O
deal O
to O
specify O
the O
properites O
to O
load O
. O

Lazy O
loading O
is O
turned O
off O
for O
validation O
, O
so O
if O
a O
property O
is O
marked O
as O
required O
and O
you O
have O
only O
loaded O
the O
parent O
an O
error O
will O
always O
be O
thrown O
which O
is O
very O
frustrating O
. O

Lazy O
loading O
also O
makes O
debugging O
rather O
tricky O
as O
the O
query O
isnt O
executed O
until O
it O
is O
used O
so O
you O
ca O
n't O
examine O
the O
results O
of O
the O
query O
as O
easily O
. O

I O
usually O
add O
a O
ToList() O
or O
similar O
to O
my O
EF O
queries O
so O
I O
can O
easily O
examine O
the O
results O
. O

. O

and O

and O

elsewhere O
. O

would O

properties O

the O
elements O

of O
your O

. O

The O
404 O
handling O
is O
completely O
different O
between O
prod B-Library_Class
and O
dev B-Library_Class
. O

In O
prod B-Library_Class
, O
the O
message O
you O
pass O
to O
the O
forward404 O
is O
simply O
written O
to O
the O

and O
not O
passed O
to O
the O
handler O
action O
. O

There O
are O
many O
ways O
to O
get O
round O
this O
, O
but O
the O
quickest O
( O
albeit O
dirtiest O
) O
would O
be O
to O
store O
the O
message O
in O
a O
static B-Data_Type
variable O
somewhere O
so O
the O

handler O
can O
access O
it O
once O

process O
gets O
there O
, O

. O

your O

( O

for O
annotation O
) O

CODE_BLOCK O
: O
A_411 O
( O
code O
omitted O
for O
annotation O
) O

Will O
catch O
and O
rethrow O
only O
exceptions B-Library_Class
derived O
from O
Exception B-Library_Class
. O

Will O
catch O
and O
rethrow O
any O
exception B-Library_Class
. O

( O
Edit O
: O
Since O
CLRv2 B-Library
, O
all O
exceptions B-Library_Class
are O
derived O
from O
Exception B-Library_Class
so O
this O
is O
identical O
to O
1 O
. O

See O
Eric O
Lippert O
's O
comment O
below O
) O
. O

Will O
catch O
any O
exception B-Library_Class
derived O
from O
Exception B-Library_Class
and O
throw O
it O
again O
, O
thus O
resetting O
the O
stack O
trace O
of O
the O
exception B-Library_Class
. O

Answer_to_Question_ID O
: O
6723135 O

Question_URL O
: O
https://stackoverflow.com/questions/6723135/ O


There O
is O
no O
difference O
between O
example O
1 O
and O
2 O
. O

Both O
rethrows O
the O
original O
exception B-Library_Class
, O
and O
both O
catches O
the O
general O
Exception B-Library_Class
. O

You O
would O
use O
example O
1 O
if O
you O
wanted O
to O
catch O
a O
more O
specific O
exception B-Library_Class
, O
such O
as O
DivisionByZeroException B-Library_Class
. O

For O
the O
last O
example O
, O
you O
are O
not O
re-throwing O
the O
exception B-Library_Class
; O
but O
throwing O
the O
same O
exception B-Library_Class
object O
that O
you O
caught O
. O

This O
causes O
the O
exception B-Library_Class
stacktrace O
to O
be O
re-set O
to O
the O
location O
where O
you O
throw O
it O
- O
which O
might O
be O
a O
problem O
because O
the O
stacktrace O
then O
does O
not O
point O
to O
the O
location O
in O
code O
, O
where O
the O
error O
actually O
occured O
. O

. O

The O
term O
' O
NP-hard O
optimization O
problem O
' O
seems O
a O
bit O
too O
broad O
to O
let O
a O
satisfying O
answer O
be O
found O
. O

For O
instance O
, O
I O
ca O
n't O
see O
what O
precludes O
decision O
problems O
from O
being O
considered O
NP-hard O
optimization O
problems O
- O
if O
you O
consider O
, O
say O
, O
the O
MAX-CNF-SAT O
problem O
with O
the O
solutions O
being O
scored O
as O
floor(k/N) O
, O
where O
k O
is O
the O
number O
of O
satisfied O
clauses O
and O
N O
is O
the O
total O
number O
of O
clauses O
in O
the O
instance O
( O
which O
is O
clearly O
computable O
in O
polynomial O
time O
) O
, O
then O
any O
valuation O
which O
yields O
a O
1 O
in O
this O
formula O
will O
have O
to O
satisfy O
the O
whole O
formula O
. O

So O
let O
's O
assume O
that O
we O
are O
maximizing O
floor(k/N) O
and O
call O
this O
the O
FLOOR-CNF-SAT O
optimization O
problem O
: O
) O

This O
implies O
you O
can O
reduce O
TAUTOLOGY O
to O
said O
optimization O
problem O
- O
negate O
the O
input O
and O
add O
any O
solution O
as O
S O
. O
You O
can O
even O
add O
a O
dummy O
variable O
to O
make O
sure O
the O
initial O
solution O
is O
gets O
a O
0 O
in O
the O
FLOOR-CNF-SAT O
problem O
. O

Negation O
is O
polynomial O
in O
time O
. O

Then O
if O
a O
solver O
for O
the O
proposed O
problem O
deems O
S O
to O
not O
be O
optimal O
, O
there O
must O
clearly O
be O
a O
valuation O
which O
yields O
a O
1 O
according O
to O
our O
crafted O
function O
and O
thus O
satisfies O
the O
whole O
formula O
- O
in O
turn O
providing O
a O
valuation O
that O
does O
not O
satisfy O
the O
original O
input O
to O
TAUTOLOGY O
. O

By O
cheating O
slightly O
( O
using O
an O
artificially O
crafted O
optimization O
problem O
) O
we O
have O
established O
the O
' O
is O
optimal O
' O
problem O
as O
co-NP-complete O
, O
since O
TAUTOLOGY O
is O
easily O
shown O
to O
be O
co-NP-complete O
. O

By O
your O
own O
argument O
the O
' O
is O
optimal O
' O
decision O
problem O
is O
co-NP-hard O
, O
since O
as O
a O
witness O
you O
only O
need O
a O
better O
solution O
- O
score O
S O
, O
score O
the O
witness O
and O
compare O
. O

I O
do O
n't O
really O
feel O
great O
about O
this O
reduction O
but O
I O
ca O
n't O
easily O
improve O
on O
the O
problem O
class O
. O

If O
you O
require O
that O
there O
be O
instances O
which O
score O

not O
just O
{ O
0 O
, O
1} O

N O

. O

problem O

NP-hard O

. O

I O

: O

Consider O

CODE_BLOCK O

) O

. O

As O

, O

Internal.Job.Filename.Directory O
is O
only O
set O
when O
you O
do O
n't O
use O
a O
repository O
, O
and O
it O
is O
set O
automatically O
. O

You O
cannot O
set O
it O
manually O
. O

How O
not O
to O
use O
an O
repository O
? O

When O
you O
start O
Spoon B-Application
, O
you O
get O
a O
dialog B-User_Interface_Element
which O
asks O
for O
a O
repository O
. O

Just O
close O
this O
dialog O
with O
cancel O
and O
you O
're O
fine O
! O

It O
took O
me O
a O
while O
to O
find O
this O
: O
I O
was O
wondering O
why O
Internal.Job.Filename.Directory O
was O
always O
empty O
. O

The O
repository O
was O
the O
cause O
. O

It O
's O
documented O
here O
: O
http://jira.pentaho.com/browse/PDI-7434 O

The O

you O
're O
linking O
to O
uses O
Web B-Library
Audio I-Library
, O
but O
it O
does O

to O

the O

of O

song O
. O

Instead O

separately O
, O

. O

: O

( O

omitted O
for O

) O

to O

( O

omitted O
for O

) O

is O

If O
all O
you O
need O
to O
do O
is O
read O
and O
write O
it O
then O
std::string B-Library_Class
is O
fine O
. O

CODE_BLOCK O
: O
A_576 O
( O
code O
omitted O
for O
annotation O
) O

This O
works O
because O
no O
multi-character O
UTF O
codepoint O
overlaps O
with O
an O
an O
ASCII O
character O
so O
the O
standard O
processing O
of O
text O
works O
just O
fine O
in O
relation O
to O
end O
of O
line O
sequence O
and O
there O
is O
no O
other O
processing O
done O
by O
the O
stream O
. O

What O
you O
read O
is O
what O
you O
get O
. O

Outputting O
the O
string B-Data_Type
does O
not O
change O
any O
of O
the O
codepoints O
. O

Now O
if O
you O
need O
to O
manipulate O
the O
text O
that O
is O
a O
different O
question O
and O
gets O
more O
complex O
. O

Usually O
manipulating O
UTF-8 O
is O
way O
to O
hard O
( O
can O
be O
done O
but O
not O
worth O
it O
IMO O
) O
. O

When O
it O
comes O
to O
manipulating O
the O
text O
you O
want O
to O
convert O
the O
UTF-8 O
( O
which O
is O
not O
a O
fixed O
width O
) O
to O
an O
internal O
fixed O
width O
format O
; O
( O
UTF-16 O
or O
UTF-32 O
are O
common O
formats O
for O
manipulation O
and O
easy O
to O
use O
; O
( O
UTF-16 O
windows B-Operating_System
, O
UTF-32 O
for O
most O
* B-Operating_System
nix I-Operating_System
like O
OS O
) O
) O
. O

The O
easiest O
way O
to O
do O
this O
is O
to O
imbue O
the O
stream O
with O
a O
facet O
that O
knows O
the O
input O
is O
in O
UTF-8 O
and O
will O
convert O
it O
automatically O
. O

There O
are O
a O
couple O
of O
these O
facets O
floating O
around O
in O
different O
libraries O
. O

But O
an O
easy O
one O
to O
find O
is O
boost O
: O

http://www.boost.org/doc/libs/1_38_0/libs/serialization/doc/codecvt.html O

Note O
: O
It O
is O
also O
in O
the O
latest O
version O
of O
boost B-Library
1.46 O

CODE_BLOCK O
: O
A_577 O
( O
code O
omitted O
for O
annotation O
) O

The O
processes O
is O
the O
same O
for O
writting O
UTF-16/32 O
back O
to O
a O
stream O
and O
converting O
it O
to O
UTF-8 O

CODE_BLOCK O
: O
A_578 O
( O
code O
omitted O
for O
annotation O
) O

Note O
. O

You O
should O
imbue O
the O
file O
before O
it O
is O
opened O
. O

Different O
implementations O
of O
the O
stream O
will O
react O
differently O
if O
you O
imbue O
the O
stream O
after O
it O
is O
open O
. O

Thus O
it O
is O
best O
to O
imbue O
the O
stream O
before O
opening O
it O
. O

Dinkumware O
also O
has O
a O
set O
of O
conversion O
facets O
( O
not O
sure O
if O
they O
are O
free O
) O
. O

http://www.dinkumware.com/manuals/default.aspx?manual=compleat&page=index_cvt.html#Code%20Conversions O

Note O
: O
I O
prefer O
to O
use O
the O
terms O
UTF-X O
rather O
than O
UCS-Y O
. O

Though O
technically O
there O
are O
very O
minor O
differences O
these O
are O
inconsequential O
compared O
to O
the O
confusion O
you O
can O
create O
by O
switching O
between O
the O
two O
terms O
while O
talking O
about O
the O
subject O
. O

Stick O
to O
one O
unless O
you O
need O
to O
talk O
explicitly O
about O
a O
feature O
( O
like O
Surrogate O
pairs O
) O
. O
